    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "KEEP \"impels\" — Chinese is genuinely stronger in footnote",
    "content": "**KEEP \"impels\"**\n\nThe Chinese is genuinely different in the two locations. The body text uses 想要 (wanting), which is volitional and softer — \"moves me to want to\" is right there. The footnote uses 推动, which is a push, a drive, a force that acts on you — it has the character of compulsion rather than inclination. \"Impels\" captures exactly this: to be impelled is to be driven by a force not fully under one's control, which is what 推动 conveys.\n\nFrom an existentialist standpoint, this distinction matters. The body text describes a phenomenal wanting (closer to Sartre's project — I orient myself toward the other). The footnote describes a phenomenal driving force (closer to what Heidegger calls Befindlichkeit — a mood or attunement that moves me before I choose). Collapsing the two into \"moves\" would erase a real difference in the original. The author chose different words; we should honor that."
  }
}
